title: For Sale:  Chris Reeves "Yarborough" knife
postcontent:
the 7 inch blade version of the "Yarborough" knife issued to Special Forces soldiers upon graduation. SF operators get the serialized 5.5 blade. The Sheath is used but the knife has never been fielded or used, and has the factory sharpening. Overall length is 12 inches. below is the write up on this knife from the Chris Reeve website. Text to REDACTED. The sheath is used but the knife is not. You can get a new sheath for it if you want but the asking price is the same. 

 "Efficient, Tough, Exceptional." Words that describe the men of the U.S. Army Special Forces and the knife designed specifically for them.

 This knife is known to the U.S. Army Special Forces as "The Yarborough" and to everyone else as "The Green Beret Knife". It is a no-nonsense, hardworking tool, designed by renowned knife maker and designer Bill Harsey, with function and manufacturing input from Chris Reeve. Made in Boise, Idaho by Chris Reeve Knives, the Green Beret Knife is a using knife that, just like the men for whom it was designed, is efficient, tough and uncompromising. 

 Without the name "Yarborough" and non-serialized, the otherwise identical knife - The Green Beret Knife - is available from Chris Reeve Knives. The Green Beret Knife is offered with either a 7” or 5.5” blade; the handle is the same size. The handle is made of extremely durable, textured, black canvas Micarta. When the handle is wet, the canvas fibers swell which increases grip. If the handle becomes dirty, it can be cleaned with a brush and a household cleaner like Soft Scrub.

title: For Sale:  Remote Trap/Clay Thrower/Launcher
postcontent:
For sale is a remotely controlled single throw clay/trap launcher.

I built this as a project and now that it is complete I want to sell it so I can fund other projects.

The thrower is a standard string operated single clay launcher from Dick's Sporting Good purchased a couple of months ago. The remote is a 1 channel single button relay operating a super tough linear actuator (for automatic car door locks). Push the button and the remote triggers the actuator, and the actuator pulls releases the throwing arm. The electronics are housed in a conduit box with a removable face plate to give access to the mount and relay.

The project it 99% complete, it operates perfectly and safely. If someone were to come up with a better setup for the release point it could be a little smoother in the "arming/loading" phase of operation. However, it works just fine as it is.

I'm including the thrower ($35), the remote relay/actuator/trigger (over $40 for parts/mounting hardware), the spare tire that the whole setup is mounted on ($40), and 2x 6v batteries (used in series for 12v). All for $100. I'll also give you whatever random odds and ends (misc hardware in 3/8 hex and 1/16 hex) I ended up with at the completion of the project if you want them. The setup is SUPER simple, hook up red to positive and white to negative and push the button to fire. The tire stabilizes everything and in my field tests doesn't move at all. Stakes in the pictures are part of another project and not included.

Call or text Ben at REDACTED

title: For Sale:  1978 Ford F-250 Camper Special
postcontent:
I have my F-250 Supercab for sale.  This truck is an awesome piece of truck history. The truck is in great condition for its age, and it has great bones for an enthusiast who wants to restore it to its former glory.  Why bother with a rusted out piece of junk, when you can go straight to painting and interior work?  You can save thousands just from not having to fool with the rust.  This truck only needs a paint job, very minor body work, and an interior overhaul to be ready for the road.  The tires are older but have lots of tread and have held up to me driving it on the interstate several times this summer.

There is only one rusted through place on the entire truck; over the DS door, on the cab, there is a rusted out place about an inch wide and 10 inches long.  I have no idea why it rusted here and not the cab corners, etc.  The rockers, fenders, bed, hood, and floorpans are all in great condition.  There is a small dent in one of the fenders, and there is a small cut/dent in the tailgate leading edge.  I will post pictures of all of these areas once I have time to take them.

The interior rubber floormat is in very good condition, and the vinyl seat covers for the front and rear seat are, as well, albeit a bit dated in color.

Here is the story:

I purchased from a guy who had it since 1982.  He drove it daily from S. Bibb County to RAFB until 2000 or so.  He spent thousands replacing the engine and multiple components then (radiator, hoses, etc.)  But what he did not do was replace the distributor.  Also, whoever installed the engine got the vacuum system all screwed up.  As a result, he never got it to run right.  The timing advance was inoperative, so at speeds above an idle it would act crazy.  Mileage since engine change is approximately 13,000.  Total mileage on truck is estimated at 163,000.

Since March of this year I have done the following:
new distributor
new spark plugs
new plug wires
new PVS's and vac lines
new belts
new battery and positive cable from battery to voltage regulator
new ignition module
new windshield wiper switch handle ($19!)
new front brake pads
new wheel front wheel bearings
new front brake rotors
new front flexible brake lines
new master cylinder
new brake booster
new rear brake flexible line
new rear 3" brake shoes (optional with Camper Special edition)
new rear brake wheel cylinders
new rear wheel seals
drained and replaced rear differential oil
fresh engine oil change
removed both fuel tanks, flushed and lined
new sending units for both tanks - gauge works for both tanks, but very accurate
new fill hoses for both fuel tanks
new flexible fuel lines from tanks to tank selector and from hard line to fuel filter and carb
installed new door seals
replaced center duct for A/C system (needs driver side patched) and now it blows strong
replaced FRONT and REAR sway bar bushings - drives tight on curves
topped off R134 in A/C system - system converted at some time in past prob 2000 - no leaks.

I have dozens of receipts showing work done since 2000.  No second guessing on what needs replacing.

Other features:
351M - all original and stock except for air breather and minor vacuum modifications.  EGR is still hooked up.
C6- bulletproof 3 speed automatic, shifts great, no slips, no noise.
REAR AXLE RATIO: 3.31 known as the mileage maker on a DANA 61. Rear Axle Code is 23.
This is a rare combo for this year model.
http://www.fordification.net/tech/vin_axle-rr.htm  
The truck should get much better fuel economy than most of this vintage.

What is needed:
1.) The truck is missing interior door panels; however, the good thing is you can see how solid this truck is.  There is no rust in the doors.   
2.) The seat covers are not worn, but they are ugly.
3.) The DS air conditioning vent needs to be re-plumbed.  I replaced the middle duct and the center vents blow strong, as does the PS vent.  I have not looked into the DS duct to see if it can be repaired or if it requires replacing.
4.) The carburetor is leaking down overnight.  I am thinking about replacing the carburetor prior to sale.
5.) The A/C is slightly over charged and is not functioning to specifications.  I may go ahead and have that addressed also.
6.) The exhaust system needs some work.  If the truck doesn't sell within a reasonable time frame, I will have this addressed soon.
7.) Although not sagging anywhere, the body mounts are probably original, and I would replace them before doing any serious building.

I have a clean Georgia title in hand.

So, look around for a project truck that could be a comfortable, one of kind, fix up any way that you like, kind of truck.  Some guys are taking the better specimens of this vintage and dropping 460's in them and a 4WD system.  There are no factory combinations of Supercab 4WD with 460's for this year.  After you look at the junk that has been sitting out back with trees growing through the engine compartment and rust galore, come back to mine and pick up something that you can drive home with confidence.  I have worked on several trucks from the frame up, and I can tell you the hard part of this build has already been done. 

Text me your email and I will take as many photos as you like and send them to you.

I am looking for a very reasonable $4500 for this barn find.  I may be open to trades/partial trades for the right things.  reloading supplies, atv's, Jeep CJ7, Wrangler, Jeep Chief, Jeep J10, boats, sailboat, camper, travel trailer, airplanes, tractors, implements, trailers, things that have firing pins, tools, etc.  Not interested in makeup, hair dressing equipment, women's clothing, etc.
